
Final exam project for the Information Retrieval course @ UniTS.

Implementation of LSI (Latent Semantic Indexing), 
an IR system based on the SVD (singular values decomposition) of the 
tf-idf (term frequency-inverse document frequency) matrix of terms vs documents in the corpus. 

Author: Marco Zampar @ UniTS
mail: marco.zampar@studenti.units.it

lsi.sh is the main script that manages the creation of the index, it calls, in order:

- download.py
- preprocess_parallel.sh & preprocess_parallel.py
- tf_idf.py
- svd.py
- test_queries.py
- plot_eff_vs_nrel.py

grid_search_lsi.sh was used to run different test with different hyperparameters.

Modules needed:

pandas, numpy, scipy
matplotlib
sklearn
re, unidecode, os, sys, string, json
nltk
beir # needed to load the corpus, if you want to run only test_queries.py, no need of this module
multiprocessing, tqdm # needed in preprocessing corpus, if corpus is already processed, no need of these modules

To run only the test_queries.py script:

# Assuming to be in IR_Project folder
qrels='./data/trec-covid/qrels/test.tsv'
queries='./data/trec-covid/queries.jsonl'
doc_titles='./data/trec-covid/doc_titles.csv'
svd_dir='./data/svd--1_terms-1_grams-150_components-15_min_df-0.5_max_df'
min_rel_docs='100'
n_components='150'
doc_ids='./data/tf_idf--1_terms-1_grams-15_min_df-0.5_max_df/trec-covid-tfidf_docids.json'
tfidf_vocabulary='./data/tf_idf--1_terms-1_grams-15_min_df-0.5_max_df/trec-covid-tfidf_vocabulary.json'
tfidf_values='./data/tf_idf--1_terms-1_grams-15_min_df-0.5_max_df/trec-covid-tfidf_values.npy'
out_csv='./test/test.tsv'

python test_queries.py $qrels $queries $doc_titles $svd_dir $min_rel_docs $n_components $doc_ids $tfidf_vocabulary $tfidf_values $out_csv

In the test folder:

# there are 3 fields for each query. i.e.:
`text`: "what is the origin of COVID-19", 
`query`: "coronavirus origin", 
`narrative`: "seeking range of information about the SARS-CoV-2 virus's origin, including its evolution, animal source, and first transmission into humans".

test_query.tsv # using only 'query' field to construct the query, mean performance: 0.28
test_q_text.tsv # using only 'query text' field m.p: 0.36
test_query_text_narrative.tsv # using all the fields: query text, narrative, query m.p: 0.44
test_query_text.tsv # using 'query' and 'query text' fields, m.p: 0.35

To generate the summary plot:

python plot_eff_vs_nrel.py './test/test_query.tsv' 'n_rel_docs2' 'ndcg_at_20' 'none' './test/test_query.png'

LLM were used in the deployment of the code, expecially to:

- parallelise the preprocessing of the corpus (in preprocess_parallel.py)
- use the nltk library (in utils.py)
- compute the tf-idf matrix (although the idea of adding back the 'covid19' term is mine) (in tf_idf.py)
- plot the efficiency vs the number of relevant documents (in plot_eff_vs_nrel.py)
- managing the df with statistics per query and the summary statistics (in test_queries.py)

Btw, the main use of LLM was aimed at solving syntactic aspects of the coding and not conceptual decisions.

The shell scripts that manage the entire analysis were fully thought and deployed by me.


